<article>
    <h1>In&#xAD;ter&#xAD;act with K-drama char&#xAD;ac&#xAD;ters on Tik&#xAD;Tok</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200813/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-13"><time>2020-08-13</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | TELEVISION</span>
        - <span role="byline">Jan Lee</span>
    </section>

    <p>Short-form video plat­form Tik­Tok is ex­pand­ing be­yond the memes and video chal­lenges it is known for.</p>
    <p>The plat­form has re­leased its first K-drama se­rial in col­lab­o­ra­tion with South Korean dig­i­tal chan­nel tvN-D for an im­mer­sive drama ex­pe­ri­ence called Trap.</p>
    <p>The 12-episode col­lege ro­mance thriller star­ring boy band JBJ’s Kim Dong-han and rookie ac­tress Woo Da-bi pre­miered last month.</p>
    <p>Main episodes, which are around 11 min­utes each, are aired on tvN-D’s YouTube page, while clips not in­cluded in the main episodes are up­loaded to Tik­Tok. And episode pre­views are put on Tik­Tok one week be­fore the main episodes go live on YouTube.</p>
    <p>The main char­ac­ters also have Tik­Tok ac­counts that audiences can fol­low – these ac­counts would in­ter­act with other char­ac­ters’ ac­counts.</p>
    <p>Audiences can thus track the changes in their re­la­tion­ships over the weeks and leave com­ments or tag the char­ac­ters.</p>
    <p>Ms Loh Kai Zhi, mar­ket­ing man­ager of Tik­Tok Malaysia and Sin­ga­pore, says this is meant to cre­ate a “new, im­mer­sive and en­gag­ing type of Korean drama ex­pe­ri­ence for fans, com­plete with hidden clips, per­spec­tives from the char­ac­ters and sneak pre­views across var­i­ous dig­i­tal plat­forms”.</p>
    <p>The episodes and clips are subti­tled in English and Korean.</p>
    <p>She says Tik­Tok took care to adapt the dif­fer­ent clips to each medium – with main episodes filmed hor­i­zon­tally like a con­ven­tional se­ries, while Tik­Tok clips are filmed ver­ti­cally to suit its mo­bile for­mat.</p>
    <p>Ms Loh adds: “Ver­ti­cal video for­mats are im­por­tant in en­gag­ing to­day’s audiences as well, given that 57 per cent of world­wide video plays come from mo­bile de­vices, and smart­phone users hold their phone ver­ti­cally about 94 per cent of the time – ac­cord­ing to a Tik­Tok Trends re­search study.”</p>
    <p>In­ter­ac­tive drama ex­pe­ri­ences are not new. Net­flix has re­leased the choose your own ad­ven­ture-style films Black Mir­ror: Ban­der­snatch (2018) and Un­break­able Kimmy Sch­midt: Kimmy Vs The Reverend (2020).</p>
    <p>Lo­cally, film-maker Roys­ton Tan’s anti-drug in­ter­ac­tive short film High has four pos­si­ble end­ings, all of which sug­gest a move to­wards more in­ter­ac­tive forms of sto­ries for audiences.</p>
    <p>While view­ers of Trap can­not in­flu­ence the di­rec­tion the story takes, they can col­lect what Ms Loh calls “es­sen­tial clues” of the se­ries by vis­it­ing dif­fer­ent Tik­Tok ac­counts.</p>
    <p>She adds that such a sense of in­ter­ac­tiv­ity and con­nec­tion is the “lifeblood” of Tik­Tok and that de­spite be­ing a short-form plat­form, it can be an im­por­tant player in fu­ture long-form pro­duc­tions.</p>
    <p>She says: “Tik­Tok is able to bring longer-form nar­ra­tive sto­ries to life by en­abling a whole new di­men­sion to the sto­ry­telling ex­pe­ri­ence through a multi-plat­form ap­proach.”</p>

